WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
All right, so I'm going to show you how to get started working on Shiny for Python apps.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:15.340
So this is our website, at least the website in its current state, it will be changing

00:00:15.340 --> 00:00:16.340
in the future.

00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:21.160
You don't have to install Python and install Shiny and, you know, set up a virtual end

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:26.639
and all that sort of stuff that you normally do for developing Python code.

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:30.320
You can just go to our website and click on examples, there's an examples button here

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:32.480
or it's in the bar up here.

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:34.919
So I just click on that.

00:00:34.919 --> 00:00:40.240
And this takes you right into this online Shiny for Python app editor.

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:44.439
So we've got this app code here, and it's running the application over here.

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:51.000
And I can make changes to this and say, everyone.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.799
And I click this button, rerun it, and the app is running right here.

00:00:55.200 --> 00:01:00.160
The really cool thing is that this is all running in the web browser.

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:02.680
So this isn't running on a server.

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:06.239
And you don't have to worry that if you change this code here, it's going to change something

00:01:06.239 --> 00:01:07.239
on our server.

00:01:07.239 --> 00:01:11.080
This is all running on your computer in your web browser.

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:15.279
So you can feel free to experiment with things as much as you want.

00:01:15.279 --> 00:01:20.180
Now over here, there's a whole bunch of different examples that you can look at.

00:01:20.180 --> 00:01:24.019
So it just starts off in this really basic one that has a slider and a text output.

00:01:24.019 --> 00:01:28.620
All right, I can move the slider and some of the stuff here changes.

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:33.540
But if you want to see how to do other things, you can explore the features of Shiny.

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:36.099
You can look at the examples from the side.

00:01:36.099 --> 00:01:39.779
So another basic example is an app with a plot.

00:01:39.779 --> 00:01:43.260
And it's asking me here, like, hey, do you want to discard all the changes to the files?

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:45.820
Because I edited this app a little bit.

00:01:45.820 --> 00:01:49.699
But since I'm switching to another example, I'm just going to throw that away.

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:52.660
And again, that won't hurt anything anywhere.

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:58.260
It's just in case you wanted to keep the changes on your computer, that's why it's asking you.

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:03.540
So here is an app with a plot, and I move a slider, and this histogram changes the number

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:06.199
of bins.

00:02:06.199 --> 00:02:09.339
And just so you know, you can make this a little wider.

00:02:09.339 --> 00:02:12.300
The layout changes when it's really narrow.

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:15.580
So this is a sidebar layout.

00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:22.539
And normally, when the window is wide enough, it'll show the sidebar content on the side.

00:02:22.539 --> 00:02:25.619
But if you make it narrow, then it reflows it, so it'll be on top.

00:02:25.619 --> 00:02:28.380
And that's so it'll be usable on mobile devices.

00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:30.580
We can look at other, there's other examples here.

